Architected production request workflow with state persistence and role-based actions
Architected production request workflow with state persistence and role-based actions
Good place to pause and lock in the design before we touch any backend. You've got the UI shell working (mock user switcher + role-based buttons), but right now those buttons are "dumb" — they show based only on which group you're in. The real system needs two things they don't have yet: a state machine (what stage is the request at?) and persistence (where does that state live?). Let me get those clear first, because everything else hangs off them.

Let me draw the flow you described as an actual state machine so we have one reference picture to build against.

Here's the workflow as a state machine — this single picture is what we'll build everything else around:


The single most important thing to take from this picture: a request lives in exactly one state at a time, and each state defines exactly one allowed action and exactly one group allowed to do it. That's the whole engine.

Notice what this changes about your current UI. Right now your buttons appear based only on which group you're in — so a manager always sees "Approve," even for a request that's already been approved and deployed to staging. The real rule is the product of two things:

show an action button only when request.status == <the state that action belongs to> AND currentUser.group == <the group that owns that state>

So "Approve" should only show when status is pending_manager_approval and you're a manager. "Run Staging Jenkins CI" only when status is pending_staging_ci and you're ops. This is why we need the state in the DB before the buttons can be correct — the button logic literally can't work without knowing the current state.

The data model
We'll need two tables, and the reason for two is worth understanding.

The first table, production_requests, holds the current state of each request — one row per request:

column	purpose
id	primary key
api_ref	which API this is for, e.g. api:default/chat-api
pr_link	the PR link the API team submits
title / summary	free text describing the change
requested_by	user who raised it
status	the current state (one of the 7 boxes above)
created_at / updated_at	timestamps
The second table, production_request_events, is an append-only history — one row every time anything happens:

column	purpose
id	primary key
request_id	foreign key back to the request
actor	who performed the action
action	e.g. SUBMIT, APPROVE, REJECT, RUN_STAGING_CI
from_status / to_status	the transition that happened
comment	optional note
created_at	when
Why split them? The first table answers "where is this request now?" instantly. The second answers "who did what, when?" — your audit trail. And it's the events table that makes your later goals (notifications and emails "on each step") almost free: every time you insert an event, that's the exact moment to fire a notification. You don't bolt notifications on later; they hang off this table naturally.

Before we build — three name mismatches that will bite you
Your catalog, annotations, and frontend mock users disagree with each other, and Backstage matching is exact. Worth fixing now so the role logic actually resolves:

Entity names can't contain spaces. kind: User with metadata.name: Pramod Reddy and kind: Group with metadata.name: Mlops Team will fail catalog validation. The machine name goes in metadata.name (e.g. pramod-reddy, mlops-team); the human name goes in spec.profile.displayName, which you already have.
The group is named staging-signoff-team in the catalog, but your API annotation points at staging-signoff-team ✓ while your frontend mockUsers uses qa-signoff-team. Pick one slug everywhere.
Your Component has owner: llm-team but you never defined an llm-team group (you have chat-api-team).
None of these are urgent for learning, but they're the kind of silent mismatch that makes you stare at a non-rendering button for an hour.

