Weighing Backstage UI migration strategies and frontend defaults
Good call — building the form first means you can see and feel the dev-team experience, then we wire submission to the backend once the shape of the data is settled. Let me ground one thing before we write code: Backstage's component library and which Material UI version the current frontend system uses, since that determines your imports.


Architected form component with MUI, validation, and state management approach
Architected form component with MUI, validation, and state management approach
Backstage actually has two component systems right now — the long-standing Material UI (MUI) one and the newer @backstage/ui (BUI) that's mid-migration. Both systems are supported today, with many parts of the ecosystem still using MUI while new components adopt BUI. For learning, we'll stay on MUI — it's what the vast majority of Backstage still uses, it's the best-documented, and @backstage/core-components gives us themed wrappers that match your portal automatically. That gets you a "beautiful" form for free without hand-writing CSS like your current raw <button>/<select> version. 
