Second — and this is the more common cause of "cannot find module" for a local plugin — the backend package has to actually depend on your plugin, otherwise the workspace can't resolve it. Check packages/backend/package.json for it under dependencies:

bash
grep production-requests packages/backend/package.json
If nothing comes back, add it (using the same name) and reinstall:

bash
yarn --cwd packages/backend add <the-name-from-package.json>@workspace:^
yarn install
The mental model: in a Backstage monorepo, packages/backend and plugins/* are separate workspace packages. import('some-plugin') only resolves if some-plugin is a declared dependency of the backend — the name in the import and the name in package.json must be byte-for-byte identical, and the dependency edge must exist. yarn new usually wires both for you, but if the scaffold half-finished or you renamed anything, one side gets out of sync and you get exactly this error.

After fixing, restart yarn dev (a fresh TypeScript server pickup matters — sometimes the editor caches the old "module not found" until the dev server reindexes). Then the curl tests from before should hit it. What does the "name" field actually say? If it's an unusual format I can tell you whether it's valid.

