Diagnosed duplicate Knex types and derived solution
Diagnosed duplicate Knex types and derived solution
This is a classic Backstage + Knex gotcha and the error message, though ugly, says exactly what's wrong if you read the two paths:

.../@backstage/backend-plugin-api/node_modules/knex   ← copy A
.../node_modules/knex                                  ← copy B
There are two copies of Knex's types installed. database.getClient() returns a Knex typed by copy A (the one Backstage uses internally), but your import { Knex } from 'knex' pulls in copy B. To TypeScript these are two different Knex types that happen to share a name, so passing A where B is expected fails — even though at runtime they're the same library.

The fix is to stop hard-coding which copy you mean. Instead of importing Knex yourself, derive the type from what getClient() actually returns — that way you always match Backstage's copy, whichever it is:

ts
import { DatabaseService } from '@backstage/backend-plugin-api';
import { Status } from '../workflow';

// the Knex type, taken from whatever getClient() returns — no direct 'knex' import
