Weighed Jenkins iframe versus API integration for workflow automation
Weighed Jenkins iframe versus API integration for workflow automation
For what you're building, the API approach wins, and it's not especially close — but the reason is specific to your workflow, so let me lay it out.

The deciding factor is your state machine. The whole point of the "ops runs staging Jenkins CI" step is that running it should advance the request from pending_staging_ci to pending_staging_cd, write an event row, and fire a notification. An iframe can't close that loop. If you embed the Jenkins UI and the ops engineer clicks "Build" inside it, that action happens entirely within Jenkins — your backend never finds out, so your status never moves and your history has a gap. You'd be back to manually clicking a separate "mark CI done" button anyway, which defeats the embed. With the API, your backend triggers the job and learns the result, so it can transition the state automatically on success (or hold/flag on failure). That's the integration you've been building toward.

There are also some hard practical problems with the iframe that often kill it before you even get to the UX question. Jenkins commonly sends X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN (or a frame-ancestors CSP), which means many setups simply refuse to render in an iframe at all — you get a blank box. Even when it does render, you've got cross-origin auth/cookie/SSO friction (the user may hit a separate Jenkins login), and you're dropping the whole Jenkins chrome into your otherwise-clean portal, which looks and feels bolted-on.

The honest cost of the API path is that it's more work and more to maintain. Triggering a Jenkins job isn't a single call: you POST to /job/<name>/buildWithParameters, deal with the CSRF crumb (or authenticate with a user + API token, which sidesteps the crumb), get back a queue-item URL, poll that until a build number is assigned, then poll the build until it reports SUCCESS/FAILURE. That polling-and-status-tracking is the part you're signing up to own.

One architecture note that matters regardless: the call should go backend-to-Jenkins, never frontend-to-Jenkins. Your React code hits your endpoint (e.g. POST /requests/:id/run-staging-ci), and your backend calls Jenkins with a stored credential. Doing it from the browser would mean CORS pain and, worse, exposing a Jenkins token to the client. This is the exact same shape as your existing flow — frontend → your backend → external system — so it slots in cleanly.

The sweet spot most teams land on is a hybrid that leans API: trigger and track via the API so you own the state transition and the audit trail, but store the Jenkins build URL on the event and surface it as a "View build in Jenkins ↗" link. You get automated workflow control plus a click-through to Jenkins' full log/console viewer when someone actually needs to debug — without trying to recreate Jenkins' log UI yourself.

If you only wanted to display jobs and build history (not drive a workflow), the calculus would be softer and an embed or the community @backstage-community/plugin-jenkins plugin could be fine. But since your case is "this action is a gated step that moves a request forward," you need the result in your hands, and that's the API. Want to sketch the backend trigger-and-poll endpoint when you get to the ops buttons?

