Contrasted ArgoCD's declarative GitOps model with Jenkins' imperative approach
Contrasted ArgoCD's declarative GitOps model with Jenkins' imperative approach
Yes — ArgoCD has a full REST/gRPC API and the same backend-to-ArgoCD, store-a-token, deep-link-for-detail pattern applies. But the mental model is different from Jenkins, and getting that difference right changes what your "run ArgoCD CD" step actually does.

Jenkins is imperative: you trigger a job, it runs, you get pass/fail. ArgoCD is declarative GitOps: it continuously reconciles your cluster toward a desired state described in Git. You don't really "run a deployment" — you ask ArgoCD to sync (apply the desired state) and then converge. So the result you poll for isn't a build's success/failure, it's two status fields on the Application: sync.status (Synced / OutOfSync) and health.status (Healthy / Progressing / Degraded / Missing). Your step is "done" when it's both Synced and Healthy.

Concretely, your "ops runs staging ArgoCD CD" step becomes:

The backend calls POST /api/v1/applications/{app}/sync for the relevant app — and this is exactly what those annotations you commented out in turn one were for (production-requests/staging-argocd-app, prod-argocd-app). The annotation tells the backend which ArgoCD app to sync for each environment, the same way you'll resolve the Jenkins job name. Then you poll GET /api/v1/applications/{app} until status.sync.status === 'Synced' and status.health.status === 'Healthy', and only then transition the request to the next state. Auth is a bearer token from an ArgoCD account (argocd account generate-token), stored as a backend secret.

There's one wrinkle worth knowing because it can make the "sync" call almost a no-op: ArgoCD only deploys whatever's currently in the target Git revision. The sync applies the desired state; it doesn't decide what that state is. So in a real promotion flow, something earlier writes the new image tag/manifest to Git — often the CI step or a dedicated promotion step — and the ArgoCD sync is what rolls it out. If your apps use an automated sync policy, ArgoCD will even pick up the Git change on its own, in which case your step shifts from "POST sync" to just "wait for it to report Synced + Healthy." Whether you trigger or merely wait depends on how your apps are configured.

The verdict is the same as Jenkins, and for the same reason: an iframe can't tell your state machine when the app went Healthy, so it can't advance the request. The API can. Use the hybrid — sync and poll via the API so the backend owns the transition and the event row, and store the ArgoCD app URL on the event so people can click through to ArgoCD's resource tree and live logs when they need the detail.

So your two ops steps end up structurally identical: call external system → poll for a terminal-ish status → on success, transition + event + notify. The only differences are the endpoints and what "success" means (Jenkins: build SUCCESS; ArgoCD: Synced + Healthy). That symmetry is worth leaning into — you can write one generic "external step runner" abstraction and plug Jenkins and ArgoCD in as two implementations behind it. Want to design that shared abstraction when you build the ops buttons, or keep them as two separate concrete endpoints first?

