Mechanism: open-and-merge vs API-merge
Same shape as the Jenkins/ArgoCD discussion, but with a twist that matters. If MLOps opens the link and merges in GitLab, then no one touched Backstage — so Backstage has to find out the merge happened on its own. If Backstage merges via the GitLab API (a button that calls PUT /merge_requests/:iid/merge), then Backstage performed the action and knows the result synchronously from the response.

The twist: this choice decides who performs the Backstage transition. In the API-merge case, MLOps clicks a Backstage button → Backstage merges → transitions on success (a human-triggered transition, like your current ones). In the open-and-merge case, the transition is triggered by GitLab telling Backstage later (a system-triggered transition). Your checkTransition currently assumes every transition has a human group performing it — you'll need to allow an actor of 'system' (or 'webhook') for merge-confirmation transitions. That's a real extension to the model worth deciding early.

How Backstage learns of the merge — the actual crux
Three options, and I'd lean hard on the first as your source of truth:

A GitLab webhook is the robust answer. You configure GitLab to POST a "Merge Request" event to a new backend endpoint whenever an MR changes. Your endpoint checks "is this the MR for request X, and did it just move to merged?" and if so, advances the state. This works regardless of how the merge happened — Backstage button, GitLab UI, command line, or a teammate merging out-of-band. It's push-based, so no delay. The one thing you must add is verification: GitLab signs webhooks with a secret token, and your endpoint must reject any request that doesn't carry it — otherwise anyone who finds the URL can fake "merged" and march your pipeline to production.

Polling the GitLab API ("is MR X merged yet?") is the fallback when you can't receive webhooks (firewalls, etc.). Simpler to start, but laggy and wasteful.

Synchronous API-merge gives you instant confirmation for merges Backstage initiates, but it doesn't cover out-of-band merges. So even if you offer an API-merge button for convenience, I'd still treat the webhook as the authoritative "it's merged" signal. Convenience button to do it; webhook to know it.

