Flow A — Merge button inside Backstage (API). The accordion row in awaiting_code_merge shows a "Merge PR" button; MLOps clicks, Backstage calls GitLab, the row advances. Feels slick — never leave the portal, one click, and you can gate the button with your state×role rule so it only appears for MLOps in the right state. But three UX problems bite: GitLab merges often aren't instant (pipeline-must-pass, approval rules, merge trains), so the API response frequently says "merge scheduled," not "merged" — your button can't honestly report success from that alone. Merges fail for real reasons (conflicts, failing pipeline, missing approvals), so you'd have to surface that error and send them to GitLab to fix it anyway. And you're hiding GitLab's own merge screen — the final diff, the approval checkboxes, conflict resolution — which, for a merge that leads to production, is exactly the screen people want to see one last time.

Flow B — Open in GitLab, Backstage reflects (webhook). The row shows a prominent "Open MR in GitLab ↗" button (you already have the link) plus a quiet "waiting for merge…" status. MLOps clicks through, reviews and merges in GitLab's real UI, and the webhook flips the Backstage row forward on its own. The context switch out and back is the only real downside, plus the row doesn't update on click — it updates when the webhook lands, so the UI needs to refresh itself (light polling while a request sits in a waiting/running state is the simple answer; refetch every few seconds, stop once it's terminal).

For your case I'd go Flow B as the default, and here's the UX reasoning, not just the plumbing reasoning: merging is a high-stakes, review-y action, and GitLab's merge screen is purpose-built for it in a way you'd only ever poorly reproduce. Pushing MLOps to merge there means they get conflict handling, approvals, and the final diff for free — especially valuable on the prod merge. Backstage's job in the UI becomes "point you to the right MR and honestly reflect its state," which is a smaller, more truthful surface.

A bonus that's easy to overlook: in Flow B the webhook payload tells you which GitLab user actually merged. That's better audit data than Flow A's "whoever clicked the Backstage button" — your event row records the real merger, sourced from GitLab, not from a mock dropdown.

So the build order I'd suggest: webhook first, with the UI being just a deep link plus an auto-refreshing status. That's the minimal correct version and it covers merges no matter how they happen. Then, if MLOps later says "I wish I could merge without leaving Backstage," add the API-merge button as pure convenience on top — but the webhook stays the source of truth that confirms it, because even your own API merge can come back "pending." You never end up not wanting the webhook; you sometimes end up not needing the button.

One caveat that's more environment than UX: webhooks require GitLab to reach your Backstage backend (a public URL or an open network path). If you're developing locally behind a firewall, you may need a tunnel (something like an ngrok-style forwarder) to receive them, or fall back to polling GitLab for the MR state until you're deployed somewhere reachable. Worth knowing before you wire it, since "the webhook never arrives" in local dev is almost always this and not a code bug.

