Architected local GitLab setup options with webhook tunnel solutions
Architected local GitLab setup options with webhook tunnel solutions
For a local POC the honest shortcut is: don't run GitLab on your machine unless you specifically want everything offline. Self-hosting GitLab CE works but it's a heavy container (wants ~4GB RAM and takes several minutes to boot), and it adds a webhook-networking wrinkle. Using gitlab.com (free) plus a tunnel is faster to a working end-to-end test. I'll give you both, but here's the recommended path.

The fast path: gitlab.com + a tunnel
1. Make a project and a test MR. On gitlab.com, create a project, push any dummy repo, make a branch, change a file, open a merge request. That MR's URL is exactly the kind of "PR link" your form captures.

2. Get a token. Create a Personal Access Token (User Settings → Access Tokens) with the api scope (read_api is enough if Backstage will only read MR state; you need full api if you also want the API-merge button). This is the token your backend uses to call GitLab.

3. Tell Backstage about GitLab. In app-config.yaml:

yaml
integrations:
  gitlab:
    - host: gitlab.com
      token: ${GITLAB_TOKEN}
That covers both the catalog/display side and gives your backend a configured client to read MRs.

4. Solve the webhook-reaches-localhost problem. This is the one real obstacle. gitlab.com lives on the internet and cannot POST to your localhost:7007. So you run a tunnel that gives localhost a temporary public URL:

bash
cloudflared tunnel --url http://localhost:7007
#   or
ngrok http 7007
It prints a public URL like https://something.trycloudflare.com. Your webhook target becomes https://something.trycloudflare.com/api/production-requests/<your-webhook-path>.

5. Configure the webhook (later, once the receiver exists): in the project's Settings → Webhooks, set the URL to that tunnel address, tick Merge request events, and set a Secret token (your receiver verifies it). GitLab gives you a "Test" button that fires a sample payload — handy for confirming the tunnel and endpoint are wired before you do a real merge.

The fully-local path: GitLab CE in Docker
If you want everything offline:

bash
docker run -d --name gitlab \
  -p 8929:8929 -p 2224:22 \
  --env GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG="external_url 'http://localhost:8929'" \
  gitlab/gitlab-ce:latest
Give it 3–5 minutes, then get the initial root password with docker exec gitlab cat /etc/gitlab/initial_root_password. Point Backstage's integration host at localhost:8929.

Two gotchas unique to this path. First, GitLab blocks webhooks to private/local addresses by default (SSRF protection), so you must enable Admin → Settings → Network → "Allow requests to the local network from webhooks and services." Second, the GitLab container reaching your Backstage host process means the webhook URL is http://host.docker.internal:7007/... (on Mac/Windows; on Linux you'd use the host's docker-bridge IP), not localhost, because inside the container localhost is the container itself.

The part you can test right now, before any of this
Two of the three pieces don't need GitLab set up at all:

The API/outbound direction works from localhost immediately — Backstage calling out to GitLab (read an MR, merge an MR) needs only the token, no tunnel. So you can test "can my backend read MR state?" as soon as you have a project and token.

And critically, you can develop the webhook receiver without GitLab or a tunnel by simulating the event with curl. Grab a sample GitLab "Merge Request" webhook payload (their docs have one), save it to a file, and POST it at your endpoint:

bash
curl -XPOST localhost:7007/api/production-requests/<webhook-path> \
  -H 'content-type: application/json' \
  -H 'X-Gitlab-Token: <your-secret>' \
  -d @sample-merge-event.json
This decouples the two questions that otherwise get tangled: "is my receiver logic correct?" (curl answers that, instantly, offline) versus "can GitLab actually reach me?" (the tunnel answers that). Build and debug the receiver with curl first; only then wire the real tunnel + webhook for the true end-to-end run. When the webhook "never arrives" in local dev, it's almost always the reachability half, not your code — and you'll already know your code is fine.

So the minimal POC sequence: gitlab.com project + token (5 minutes) → test the read path now → build the webhook receiver next, debugging it with curl → start a tunnel and register the real webhook → merge the test MR and watch Backstage advance. Want to build that webhook receiver endpoint next, with the secret-token verification baked in from the start?

