Validated webhook callback pattern, affirmed architectural symmetry
Validated webhook callback pattern, affirmed architectural symmetry
Yes — and honestly that's a cleaner design than my polling suggestion, especially because you already built exactly this pattern for GitLab. Jenkins becomes your second "external system that pushes events to Backstage when something completes," with the same mental model: an open endpoint, a secret-token check, find the request, let the state machine advance it, broadcast. Same code shape, same security pattern, same idempotency story. You don't learn a new pattern; you reuse the one you just validated.

The push approach has a few real wins over polling. There's no setTimeout loop sitting in your Node process waiting on a build, which means nothing weird happens if Backstage restarts mid-build — Jenkins will still POST when it's done, and Backstage will react then. The state machine stays simple: pending_staging_ci just waits until the callback arrives; you don't need a separate "running, currently polling" sub-state. And you can ship it with curl tests, exactly like the GitLab webhook.

The tradeoff is real but manageable: this approach assumes the Jenkinsfile is correctly configured to call back. If the post { success { ... } } block never runs (Jenkinsfile error, network failure, Jenkins killed mid-pipeline), Backstage waits forever — there's no "I'd better check on it" instinct. Polling would catch that; callback won't. Mitigation, if it ever bites you: a periodic safety sweep that checks Jenkins's API for any request stuck in pending_staging_ci for too long. You don't need that on day one, but worth knowing it exists as a backstop.

Here's how the pieces fit together:

Backstage still triggers the build — the post-merge callback only solves the "knowing it finished" half. So in your existing merge handler, after the state advances to pending_staging_ci and you broadcast, you fire one POST to localhost:8080/job/chat-api/buildWithParameters?requestId=<the-id>&token=<job-token>. The crucial bit is passing the request ID as a build parameter — that's how Jenkins later knows which Backstage request to call back about. Without it, the callback can't match.

Jenkinsfile carries the callback. In your job's pipeline you add something like:

post {
  success { httpRequest httpMode: 'POST', url: "${BACKSTAGE_URL}/api/production-requests/jenkins/callback", customHeaders: [[name: 'x-jenkins-token', value: env.JENKINS_CB_SECRET]], requestBody: """{"requestId": "${params.requestId}", "result": "SUCCESS", "buildUrl": "${BUILD_URL}"}""" }
  failure { httpRequest ...same but result: 'FAILURE'... }
}
(The httpRequest plugin is the standard way; curl from a sh step also works if you don't want a plugin.) That covers both branches cleanly — success advances state, failure transitions to a new failure state (or back to a pending one).

The Backstage endpoint is your GitLab-webhook handler with three letters changed. New route /jenkins/callback: verify the x-jenkins-token header against a configured secret, read requestId + result from the body, store.getById(requestId), run checkTransition('STAGING_CI_SUCCESS', ...) for SUCCESS or STAGING_CI_FAILED for FAILURE, apply, broadcast. Identical structure to what you already have — and the requestId join key is more robust than the URL match you're doing for the MR, because Jenkins is sending you back exactly the value you handed it.

Workflow changes: add two system actions, STAGING_CI_SUCCESS (from pending_staging_ci to whatever's next) and STAGING_CI_FAILED (from pending_staging_ci to a new staging_ci_failed state). Group 'system' on both, so the existing checkTransition machinery just works. Same shape as your MERGE_PR.

One small thing about the merge handler: trigger Jenkins as fire-and-forget after the response, exactly like your notifier — void triggerJenkins(updated).catch(err => logger.error(...)). You've already done the merge transition and broadcast; whether the Jenkins HTTP call succeeds or fails shouldn't roll those back. If the trigger fails, the request just sits in pending_staging_ci and you have to re-fire it (or build a retry, later). That's the same robustness model as your notifications.

