Now the unavoidable reality I flagged earlier when we discussed iframe vs API: Jenkins sends X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN by default, and your Backstage frontend (typically localhost:3000) is a different origin from Jenkins (localhost:8080). The browser will refuse to render the iframe and you'll see a blank box plus a console message like "Refused to display ... because it set X-Frame-Options to 'sameorigin'." Jenkins's flag for disabling that header has moved around between versions; the most reliable local fix is a tiny nginx in front of Jenkins that strips the header.

Run nginx in a container, point it at Jenkins, and iframe through it instead. Create nginx.conf:

nginx
server {
  listen 80;
  location / {
    proxy_pass http://host.docker.internal:8080;
    proxy_set_header Host $http_host;
    proxy_hide_header X-Frame-Options;
    proxy_hide_header Content-Security-Policy;
  }
}
bash
docker run -d -p 8081:80 --add-host=host.docker.internal:host-gateway \
  -v $(pwd)/nginx.conf:/etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf:ro nginx:alpine
That gives you Jenkins reachable at localhost:8081 without the framing headers. The iframe src above points there. Backstage's trigger call still goes direct to localhost:8080 (no framing involved on that side).

Try the iframe pointing at :8080 first if you want to confirm it's blocked in your setup — if for some reason your Jenkins is configured permissively (some plugins/versions don't send the header), you can skip the proxy. The console error is unambiguous when it bites.

