Traced dependency injection pattern for config parameter sourcing
Traced dependency injection pattern for config parameter sourcing
It comes from the deps block of registerInit — Backstage's dependency injection. You declared it earlier when we added the Mailer (which also reads SMTP settings from config), so it should already be in your plugin.ts. Here's the relevant skeleton, with the Jenkins addition in place:

ts
import { createBackendPlugin, coreServices } from '@backstage/backend-plugin-api';
import { catalogServiceRef } from '@backstage/plugin-catalog-node';
import { createRouter } from './service/router';
import { RequestsStore } from './database/RequestStore';
import { Mailer } from './notifications/Mailer';
import { Notifier } from './notifications/Notifier';
import { JenkinsClient } from './jenkins/JenkinsClient';

export const productionRequestsPlugin = createBackendPlugin({
  pluginId: 'production-requests',
  register(env) {
    env.registerInit({
      deps: {
        httpRouter: coreServices.httpRouter,
        logger:     coreServices.logger,
        database:   coreServices.database,
        config:     coreServices.rootConfig,   // <-- this is where it comes from
        catalog:    catalogServiceRef,
        auth:       coreServices.auth,
      },
      async init({ httpRouter, logger, database, config, catalog, auth }) {
        const store         = await RequestsStore.create(database);
        const notifier      = new Notifier(Mailer.fromConfig(config, logger), catalog, auth);
        const jenkinsClient = JenkinsClient.fromConfig(config, logger);

        httpRouter.use(await createRouter({ logger, store, notifier, jenkinsClient }));

        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/health',                       allow: 'unauthenticated' });
        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/requests',                     allow: 'unauthenticated' });
        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/requests/:id/transition',      allow: 'unauthenticated' });
        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/requests/:id/events',          allow: 'unauthenticated' });
        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/requests/merged',              allow: 'unauthenticated' });
        httpRouter.addAuthPolicy({ path: '/events/stream',                allow: 'unauthenticated' });
      },
    });
  },
});

export default productionRequestsPlugin;
The mental model: deps is the shopping list of services you're asking Backstage to inject. Backstage hands them to your init function as an object, and you destructure what you need. coreServices.rootConfig is Backstage's wrapped app-config.yaml reader — once you've declared it in deps, config.getConfig('productionRequests.jenkins') inside JenkinsClient.fromConfig works because it's reading from that same source.

If you check your current plugin.ts and config isn't in deps, just add the line config: coreServices.rootConfig, and destructure it in the init({ ... }) signature, and you're set.

