Architected GitLab API integration for automated issue creation and storage
Architected GitLab API integration for automated issue creation and storage
Yes — GitLab's REST API has a straightforward issue-create endpoint, so we can do this on request submission. The shape is: when someone creates a production request, the backend POSTs to GitLab to make a tracking issue in the same project as the PR, then stores the returned iid (the human-readable issue number like #3) on the request row. Later, when you trigger Jenkins, you pass that iid as a build parameter.

Five small pieces.

1. GitLab client (gitlab/GitLabClient.ts)
Mirror of JenkinsClient shape. Also includes a helper to parse the project path out of the MR URL the user submitted — saves them configuring the project separately.

ts
import { RootConfigService, LoggerService } from '@backstage/backend-plugin-api';

export class GitLabClient {
  private constructor(
    private readonly baseUrl: string,
    private readonly token: string,
    private readonly logger: LoggerService,
  ) {}

  static fromConfig(config: RootConfigService, logger: LoggerService) {
    const gitlab = config.getConfig('productionRequests.gitlab');
    const baseUrl = (gitlab.getOptionalString('baseUrl') ?? 'https://gitlab.com').replace(/\/$/, '');
    const token = gitlab.getString('apiToken');
    return new GitLabClient(baseUrl, token, logger);
  }

  // "https://gitlab.com/group/project/-/merge_requests/1" -> "group/project"
  static projectPathFromMrUrl(url: string): string | undefined {
    const m = url.match(/gitlab\.com\/(.+?)\/-\//);
    return m ? m[1] : undefined;
  }

  async createIssue(
    projectPath: string,
    input: { title: string; description?: string },
  ): Promise<{ iid: string; url: string }> {
    const encoded = encodeURIComponent(projectPath); // GitLab accepts URL-encoded "group/project" as :id
    const res = await fetch(`${this.baseUrl}/api/v4/projects/${encoded}/issues`, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'content-type': 'application/json', 'PRIVATE-TOKEN': this.token },
      body: JSON.stringify({ title: input.title, description: input.description ?? '' }),
    });
    if (!res.ok) {
      const body = await res.text().catch(() => '');
      throw new Error(`createIssue failed (${res.status}): ${body}`);
    }
    const data = await res.json();
    return { iid: String(data.iid), url: data.web_url as string };
  }
}
The iid is what you want — it's per-project, monotonically increasing, and matches what people see in the UI (#1, #2…). The plain id is the global numeric one nobody refers to. Storing iid plus web_url gives you both the number for Jenkins parameters and a clickable link for the UI.

