Diagnosed startup failure by tracing initialization errors and missing configuration
That 503 isn't your request — it's Backstage telling you the plugin's init function never finished (it's still in the "starting" phase, so the middleware refuses traffic). The 503 is just a symptom; the real error happened earlier, at startup. Scroll up in the backend's log output until you find the actual stack trace from init — it'll be near the very first lines after you ran yarn dev.

Given what we just added in the last few turns, my strong guess is missing config. Every *.fromConfig you wrote uses config.getString(...) for required keys — and getString throws synchronously if a key is missing or its env var is unresolved. That throw aborts init, leaves the plugin stuck in "starting," and every incoming request gets the 503 you're seeing.

Check app-config.yaml actually has all of these, and that each ${...} env var is exported in the shell that started the backend:

yaml
productionRequests:
  email:
    from: '...'
    smtp:
      host: localhost
      port: 1025
      secure: false

  jenkins:
    baseUrl: http://localhost:8080
    username: admin
    apiToken: ${PR_JENKINS_API_TOKEN}

  gitlab:
    apiToken: ${PR_GITLAB_API_TOKEN}
    issueProject: 'neuronhyd3-group/prod-request-tracker'   # this one is new and required
    webhookSecret: ${PR_GITLAB_WEBHOOK_SECRET}
The most likely culprit is productionRequests.gitlab.issueProject — we just added it as a required string in GitLabClient.fromConfig, and if you skipped adding it to the config, init blows up on the first request and you sit at 503 from then on.

Two quick checks:

bash
echo $PR_JENKINS_API_TOKEN
echo $PR_GITLAB_API_TOKEN
echo $PR_GITLAB_WEBHOOK_SECRET
If any come back empty in the same shell that ran yarn dev, that's it. Export them and restart. On Windows PowerShell it's $env:PR_GITLAB_API_TOKEN = '...'.

If those are all set, paste the lines from your backend log around the time production-requests was supposed to register — there'll be a real error message just above the timeout, and the fix is whatever that message names.

