Diagnosed naming convention inconsistency in data transfer object
Diagnosed naming convention inconsistency in data transfer object
A DTO stands for "Data Transfer Object" — it's a general programming pattern, not a Backstage thing. The idea: when data crosses a boundary (database ↔ application, server ↔ client, internal ↔ public API), you don't necessarily want to pass the raw shape on the inside through as-is. You translate it into a transfer-friendly shape — that translated thing is the DTO.

In your case the boundary is database row → rest of your JavaScript code (and ultimately the JSON the frontend sees). The function toDto is the translator that converts one to the other.

Now the case question. Look at any single line:

ts
apiRef: row.api_ref
There are two sides to the colon, and they mean completely different things:

The right side — row.api_ref — is reading a property from the database row. Databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite) by long-standing convention name columns in snake_case: api_ref, created_at, pr_link. That's a SQL world thing. Knex hands you the row with column names exactly as they are.

The left side — apiRef — is the key in the new object you're building. JavaScript and TypeScript by convention use camelCase: apiRef, createdAt, prLink. That's the JS world thing.

So the line apiRef: row.api_ref literally says: "in my JS-shaped output, put a key called apiRef, and fill it with the value of the snake_case api_ref column." The whole point of toDto is to do this rename, once, at the boundary — so the rest of your code never has to type row.api_ref and just uses request.apiRef everywhere.

Two conventions, two worlds, one translation layer.

Now look at your file with that lens:

ts
apiRef:                row.api_ref,                      // ✅ db: snake / js: camel
prLink:                row.pr_link,                      // ✅
issue_id:              row.issue_id,                     // ❌ js key still snake_case
issue_link:            row.issue_link,                   // ❌
branch:                row.branch,                       // — single word, looks the same either way
change_type:           row.change_type,                  // ❌
stagingManifestPrLink: row.staging_manifest_pr_link,     // ✅
requestedBy:           row.requested_by,                 // ✅
The ones marked ❌ are inconsistent. The right side is fine (it has to match the column name), but the left side broke convention — those JS keys should be issueId, issueLink, changeType. Right now your DTO emits a mix, so your frontend has to decide whether to write request.issueId or request.issue_id, which is confusing and a source of bugs (autocomplete won't help, and a typo silently becomes undefined).

The fix is just renaming the left side:

ts
issueId:    row.issue_id,
issueLink:  row.issue_link,
changeType: row.change_type,
DB columns stay snake_case (don't touch your schema). The DTO becomes consistently camelCase. The frontend uses request.issueId, request.issueLink, request.changeType — matching request.prLink, request.requestedBy, and all the rest.

That's the whole point of a DTO existing as a separate function from the raw row: it gives you exactly one place to enforce the naming convention. If it's inconsistent there, it's inconsistent everywhere.

