Good move — getting off mock users is the natural next step. Before any code, a quick port-conflict flag and then a conceptual split that matters.

Quick: 8080 is taken
Your phpldapadmin is mapped to 8080:80, but Jenkins is already on 8080. Pick something free — 8082:80 for phpldapadmin works (you've already got Jenkins on 8080 and the nginx-strips-headers proxy on 8081). Otherwise the phpldapadmin container will fail to bind or shadow Jenkins.

Two layers of "LDAP auth" — they're separate decisions
People say "use LDAP" and mean one of two things, and Backstage treats them as completely independent:

LDAP as the source of users and groups (catalog ingestion). Backstage's @backstage/plugin-catalog-backend-module-ldap connects to your LDAP server, pulls Users and Groups, and writes them into the catalog replacing the YAML you've been hand-maintaining. This is what makes "the four mock users" become real, refreshable, queryable entities. Doesn't require anyone to log in — it's purely data import.

LDAP as the way people sign in (authentication). A user types their LDAP username/password into Backstage and a session gets minted. Backstage doesn't ship a first-party LDAP sign-in provider; the usual paths are (a) front LDAP with Keycloak/Authentik (LDAP→OIDC), and Backstage uses the OIDC provider, or (b) write a custom auth resolver, or (c) skip real sign-in for now and stay on the guest provider for local dev while the catalog half works.

