Diagnosed LDAP tree visibility issue and formulated troubleshooting steps
Two things to check, in order, because "no tree" can mean either the directory is genuinely empty or you haven't actually logged in.

First, confirm you're logged in. Before login, phpldapadmin's left pane just shows a "login" link, not the directory tree. Click it, enter:

Login DN: cn=admin,dc=npci,dc=local
Password: admin
After successful login, the left pane shows dc=npci,dc=local as the root node with a triangle/plus to expand it. If the only thing you see is "login," that's all that's wrong.

Second, confirm the directory actually has data. Even after logging in, if no LDIF was loaded, the base DN node won't have any children to expand — there's nothing under it. Check from the command line:

bash
docker exec ldap ldapsearch -x -D "cn=admin,dc=npci,dc=local" -w admin \
  -b "dc=npci,dc=local" "(objectClass=*)" dn
Three possible outcomes:

If you see only one or two dn: lines for dc=npci,dc=local and cn=admin,..., the directory is empty — the bootstrap LDIF never loaded. Run it:

bash
docker cp bootstrap.ldif ldap:/tmp/bootstrap.ldif
docker exec ldap ldapadd -x -D "cn=admin,dc=npci,dc=local" -w admin \
  -f /tmp/bootstrap.ldif -H ldap://localhost:389
Watch the output carefully — any error (already exists, no such attribute, invalid syntax) names the exact LDIF entry that failed. Fix and re-run.

If you see all eight extra dn: lines (two OUs, four users, four groups), the data is there and phpldapadmin should be showing it — try logging out and back in to force the tree to refresh.

If ldapsearch itself errors with "No such object" for the base DN, the OpenLDAP container didn't initialize the directory. Easiest fix is to nuke its volume and let it bootstrap fresh:

bash
docker compose down -v
docker compose up -d
# then re-run the ldapadd above
