OK, focusing on functionality and correctness. There's one significant logic gap, plus a handful of smaller issues. Let me walk through them in order of how much they'll bite.

The big one: groups aren't actually wired to users
Your LDAP config ingests users only:

yaml
catalog:
  providers:
    ldapOrg:
      default:
        users:
          - dn: ou=People,dc=npci,dc=local
        # Groups come from the git-hosted groups.yaml location below.
…and groups come from a static YAML at a GitLab URL. That works fine for defining the four groups as catalog entities, but it doesn't connect users to groups. Your role gating in the UI (currentUser.group === 'manager-approvers') needs the user-to-group relationship to come from somewhere. Right now nothing populates it:

The LDAP module isn't reading group memberships (no groups: section under ldapOrg.default), so the member attributes you put on groupOfNames in the LDIF are being ignored.
Your static groups.yaml presumably lists groups but doesn't enumerate spec.members (and even if it did, hand-maintaining that defeats the point of LDAP).
Result: every user comes in with empty memberOf, every UI gate fails closed, the app looks logged-in but nothing's permitted.

Fix: add a groups section so LDAP reads them and the member DNs resolve to user references:

yaml
catalog:
  providers:
    ldapOrg:
      default:
        target: ldap://localhost:389
        bind:
          dn: cn=admin,dc=npci,dc=local
          secret: admin
        users:
          - dn: ou=People,dc=npci,dc=local
            options:
              filter: (objectClass=inetOrgPerson)
            map:
              rdn: uid
              name: uid
              displayName: cn
              email: mail
        groups:
          - dn: ou=Groups,dc=npci,dc=local
            options:
              filter: (objectClass=groupOfNames)
            map:
              rdn: cn
              name: cn
              description: description
              type: groupType
              displayName: cn
              members: member
The members: member line is the one that does the real work — it tells the module "for each group entity, look at the LDAP member attribute (which holds full user DNs) and link those to the corresponding User entities by DN." After this, users come in with memberOf populated and your gates start working.

Once this is on, you can drop the GitLab-hosted groups.yaml location entirely — LDAP becomes the single source of truth, which is what you wanted in the first place. If you want to keep the GitLab YAML around as a backup, narrow its rules: allow: to just User or remove it; otherwise you'll end up with two providers fighting over the same group names.

The name-mapping double override
You have three places trying to set the user entity name:

catalog.providers.ldapOrg.users.map.name: uid → name = pramod.reddy (the uid).
ldapUserTransform.ts → overrides name to email local-part = pramod.reddy (again).
The LDAP auth resolver returns { uid: username.split('@')[0] } → pramod.reddy.
All three happen to produce the same string because your LDIF has uid = email local-part. So nothing breaks today. But it means the transformer file is doing zero useful work — the map.name: uid already gets you what you want. If you ever onboard a user whose uid differs from their email local-part, you'll get a silent mismatch between the catalog name (from map.name) and what the transformer wants to set, and you'll spend time debugging which won. Pick one and delete the other; the simplest cut is to delete ldapUserTransform.ts entirely and remove its backend.add(...) line.

Smaller things in ldapAuthExt.ts
ts
deps: { config: coreServices.rootConfig, ldapAuth: ldapAuthExtensionPoint },
async init({ ldapAuth }) {
config is in deps but never destructured — harmless but a lint warning. Drop it from deps until you actually use it:

ts
deps: { ldapAuth: ldapAuthExtensionPoint },
Same shape inside the resolver — password and options are unused parameters. The plugin does the actual LDAP bind/credential check before this resolver runs, so you don't need them; you can prefix unused names with _ to silence the lint:

ts
async ldapAuthentication(username, _password, _options) {
  return { uid: username.split('@')[0] };
},
And checkUserExists: async () => true is OK for POC but it means any username that LDAP authenticates is accepted as a Backstage identity, even if the catalog doesn't contain a matching User entity. Once catalog ingestion is working (after the groups fix), tighten this to actually look the user up — otherwise you can authenticate but the rest of Backstage may not recognize the identity.

app-config.yaml consistency thing
You have:

yaml
auth:
  providers:
    ldap:
      development:
        ...
But the @immobiliarelabs/backstage-plugin-ldap-auth-backend plugin typically registers itself under a fixed provider id — and the key under auth.providers has to match whatever that id is. If the plugin's id is ldap, you're fine. If it's ldap-auth or anything else, the plugin won't find its config and silently use defaults (or fail to start). Worth verifying against that plugin's docs — the symptom of a mismatch is "login button does nothing" or "provider not found" in the backend logs.

Also, auth.providers.guest: {} is still on. That's deliberate for local dev (it lets you fall back to guest while LDAP is being debugged), but worth knowing it's there — once LDAP works end to end you'll want to remove it so the only way in is the LDAP login.

