No — and this is the exact confusion the "two layers" point from a few turns back was trying to head off. Let me unpack it because it matters.

Authentication and the catalog are two separate systems in Backstage that happen to share concepts.

Authentication is "did this person prove they're who they say they are." That happens in the @immobiliarelabs/backstage-plugin-ldap-auth-backend plugin you installed. When someone types pramod.reddy@npci.org.in + password and hits sign-in, that plugin does an LDAP bind against ldap://localhost:389 and asks the LDAP server "are these credentials valid?" If yes, login succeeds. Then your resolver runs and returns { uid: 'pramod.reddy' }.

Notice what that flow never touched: the Backstage catalog. The auth plugin reads directly from LDAP at login time. It does not read from the catalog. It does not care whether the catalog has a User entity for that person.

The @backstage/plugin-catalog-backend-module-ldap module is a different thing. It periodically scrapes LDAP and copies users into the catalog as User entities — so that other catalog-aware features (ownership, search, the Users page) can see them. It has nothing to do with whether sign-in works.

So: you can absolutely sign in via LDAP with the catalog LDAP provider deleted. The auth plugin talks to LDAP directly; the catalog module is a separate, optional data-copying job.

Why you should delete it anyway, in your model.

You're sourcing Users and their group membership from YAML. That means YAML is creating User entities with metadata.name: pramod.reddy and spec.memberOf: [chat-api-team]. If the LDAP catalog module is also running, it's also creating a User entity for the same person, with whatever transformer mapping you wrote. You now have two providers writing the same User entity — same metadata.name. One of these things happens:

They write identical entities and Backstage logs duplicate warnings on every refresh.
They write different entities (LDAP-sourced has no memberOf because LDAP doesn't have your groups; YAML-sourced has the right memberOf). Whichever processor runs second overwrites the other. Race condition. Sometimes your user has groups, sometimes they don't, depending on refresh timing.
In either case, your YAML's group membership is at risk of being silently wiped by the LDAP module's "I don't see any groups in LDAP, so this user is in no groups" view.

The mental model to lock in.

Layer	Who owns it	Where does the data live
Authentication (sign-in)	ldap-auth-backend	Talks live to LDAP at login
Catalog Users	Catalog YAML	Static YAML files
Catalog Groups	Catalog YAML	Static YAML files
The login flow reaches the LDAP container directly. The catalog never enters the picture during sign-in. After sign-in succeeds, checkUserExists does look in the catalog — and at that point your YAML-sourced User has to be there. But the auth-LDAP↔catalog-LDAP link doesn't exist; they're independent.

So: delete the catalog.providers.ldapOrg block, delete the catalog LDAP plugin from backend.add(...), and your sign-in continues to work exactly as before. The catalog stops being a contested space, your YAML-sourced groups stay intact, and the role gating actually behaves.

