ldapAuthExt.ts is the sign-in resolver. The ldapAuthentication callback runs after LDAP successfully verifies the password — so its only job is to map the typed username (an email) to a stable Backstage identity. username.split('@')[0] does exactly that, the same way the transformer does, so the two systems agree on the name. checkUserExists currently returns true unconditionally, which means "anyone whose LDAP password works gets a session, even if they're not in the catalog." For a POC that's fine — but once the LDAP→catalog ingestion is on, you can tighten it to actually look the user up. The cleaner version, since you want the catalog as source of truth:

ts
import { coreServices, createBackendModule } from '@backstage/backend-plugin-api';
import { catalogServiceRef } from '@backstage/plugin-catalog-node';
import { ldapAuthExtensionPoint } from '@immobiliarelabs/backstage-plugin-ldap-auth-backend';

export default createBackendModule({
  pluginId: 'auth',
  moduleId: 'ldap-ext',
  register(reg) {
    reg.registerInit({
      deps: {
        ldapAuth: ldapAuthExtensionPoint,
        catalog: catalogServiceRef,
        auth: coreServices.auth,
      },
      async init({ ldapAuth, catalog, auth }) {
        ldapAuth.set({
          resolvers: {
            async ldapAuthentication(username, _password, _options) {
              return { uid: username.split('@')[0].toLowerCase() };
            },
            async checkUserExists(uid) {
              const credentials = await auth.getOwnServiceCredentials();
              const entity = await catalog.getEntityByRef(
                `user:default/${uid}`,
                { credentials },
              );
              return !!entity;
            },
          },
        });
      },
    });
  },
});
Two small upgrades: lowercase the uid (Backstage entity names can't have uppercase, so this defensively normalizes), and checkUserExists actually queries the catalog so an LDAP user not in the catalog gets a clean "no" instead of a confusing fully-authenticated-but-permission-less session. Same goes for the name: email.split('@')[0] in the transformer — apply .toLowerCase() there too so they stay consistent.

So: yes, both modules are correctly designed for the model you've landed on. The transformer is the bridge from LDAP-native shape to Backstage-name shape; the resolver is the bridge from typed username to the same Backstage name. Their job is to keep one identifier consistent across three boundaries (LDAP, catalog, session).

