Now the part to understand, because it's the part you didn't say you knew: the map: section asks "which LDAP attribute provides the value for each Backstage User field?" Left side = Backstage field, right side = LDAP attribute name. Same shape as the DTO we did earlier — left is the target schema, right is the source data.

Walking through it:

rdn: uid — "use the uid attribute as the entry's relative distinguished name." Effectively says "the unique identifier within ou=People is the uid attribute." If your users have a different attribute that uniquely identifies them, swap it. For 99% of LDAPs using inetOrgPerson, uid is correct.

name: uid — "set the Backstage User's metadata.name from the LDAP uid attribute." This is the one that becomes pramod.reddy in your catalog. If your LDAP uid is the email local-part already (which yours is, by design), this is fine. If your real LDAP has uids like employee numbers (E12345) but you want names like pramod.reddy, this is where the ldapUserTransform.ts module steps in to override it — that's what your transformer is for.

displayName: cn — "set the User's spec.profile.displayName from the LDAP cn (Common Name) attribute." cn is the standard LDAP attribute for "full name as you'd display it," e.g. Pramod Reddy. That shows up in the UI header, "Logged in as Pramod Reddy."

email: mail — "set the User's spec.profile.email from the LDAP mail attribute." mail is the standard LDAP attribute name for email addresses (it's literally just called mail, not email). You said you "have an email attribute" — if when you ldapsearch your users, the line is mail: someone@npci.org.in, you're good as-is. If your org's schema names it something else (like userPrincipalName in Active Directory, or email, or emailAddress), that's what goes on the right.

So in plain English: the only thing you'd ever change in map: is if your LDAP names attributes differently from the defaults. The defaults match the standard inetOrgPerson schema, which is what your osixia/openldap container uses, so this block as written is correct for your setup.

The options.filter: (objectClass=inetOrgPerson) line is "only ingest LDAP entries that have objectClass: inetOrgPerson." That excludes the admin entry, OUs, and anything else that isn't a person. Standard LDAP filter syntax; this catches all your users from the LDIF.

The one place this connects back to the auth side: usernameAttribute: 'mail' in the auth.providers.ldap.development.ldapAuthenticationOptions block. That tells the auth plugin "when someone types something into the login box, look up the LDAP entry whose mail attribute equals that string, then try to bind as that entry." You set that to mail because you want users to log in with their email. If you wanted them to log in with their uid, you'd change it to uid. Same attribute name as on the right side of map.email.

So you have everything you need. Drop the values in, restart, and the LDAP module will print on startup how many users it ingested — if it says zero, the filter or DN is wrong; if it says four, you're done.

