Let me address both — the config file first since you'll hit those issues on startup, then the resolver question.

Issues in this config
target needs the protocol scheme. It's ldaps://10.88.1.121:636 (or ldap:// for unencrypted), not bare host:port. Port 636 is the standard LDAPS (TLS) port, so:

yaml
target: ldaps://10.88.1.121:636
Typos in the bind DN. You have CM=Hadoop Admin — should be CN= (Common Name, not CM). Spaces inside a CN value are legal but commonly quoted to be safe: CN="Hadoop Admin".

Two typos in the filter that will silently match nothing. The line:

yaml
filter: (objectlass=user)(sAMAccountName={0})
has objectlass (missing c → not a real attribute), and the two clauses aren't joined into a single LDAP expression — LDAP filters with multiple conditions must be wrapped with a boolean operator. Also, {0} placeholder substitution exists in the auth plugin's usernameAttribute-style query, not in the catalog provider's filter (the catalog ingests everyone, no per-user substitution). Drop the second clause for ingestion. So:

yaml
filter: (&(objectClass=user)(!(objectClass=computer)))
Active Directory has computers, contact objects, and service accounts all sharing objectClass=user — the !(objectClass=computer) exclusion is the standard way to pull just human accounts. If your OU only contains humans you can simplify to (objectClass=user).

The map: block needs AD attribute names, not LDAP standards. Your earlier osixia OpenLDAP is OpenLDAP-flavored; this one is Active Directory, which uses different attribute names. The schema is:

Backstage field	AD attribute
rdn	cn (or sAMAccountName)
name	sAMAccountName — the short login name like pramod.reddy
displayName	displayName (yes, AD has an attribute literally named that)
email	mail
