One more LDAPS-specific gotcha worth knowing in advance: if your AD server uses an internal CA, Node will refuse the TLS handshake by default (untrusted issuer). Two ways through: ship the CA cert to the Backstage host and point NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS at it (clean), or set NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0 in development (lazy, only for local). If the backend logs show unable to verify the first certificate on LDAP refresh, that's the symptom.

Can you skip the resolver and read x.y directly from LDAP?
Yes — and with AD specifically, you almost should, because AD has a perfect attribute for it. The reason the resolver existed in your OpenLDAP setup was that the typed username (an email) needed converting to the entity name (the local part) — pramod.reddy@npci.local → pramod.reddy. Your transformer did the same on the ingest side.

In AD, sAMAccountName is already that short login name — pramod.reddy, no @ in it. If you have the user log in with sAMAccountName instead of email, no transformation is needed at all. The string they type is the entity name.

So you can collapse the whole identity bridge:

In the map: block above, name: sAMAccountName already makes the catalog entity name pramod.reddy.

In the auth provider block, set usernameAttribute: 'sAMAccountName' (instead of mail) — now sign-in looks up users by their short name.

In your resolver, the username passed in is already pramod.reddy, so the body becomes the identity — no split needed:

ts
async ldapAuthentication(username, _password, _options) {
  return { uid: username.toLowerCase() };
},
Strictly speaking the resolver function is still there (the plugin needs one), but it has nothing to do. The whole split('@')[0] ceremony goes away.

Even cleaner: you can also delete ldapUserTransform.ts entirely. Its job was to overwrite the catalog name with the email local-part because the LDAP uid didn't match it. In AD with name: sAMAccountName, the catalog name is already what you want.

The mental model worth taking from this: the resolver and the transformer only exist to bridge name mismatches across the LDAP↔catalog↔login boundary. If you choose one identifier that's the same string in all three places — and AD gives you sAMAccountName for free — both pieces of bridging code become no-ops you can delete.

The one case where you'd want to keep the email-based login is if your org culturally types email addresses to log in everywhere (most do, with Office 365 SSO etc.). If that's the case, you can do usernameAttribute: 'userPrincipalName' instead (AD's email-shaped login attribute), and keep the resolver/transformer doing the split('@')[0] work. Pick based on what users actually type — if they prefer email, keep the bridges; if short-name login is fine for an internal portal, delete them.

So to sum the design choices: with your AD config corrected, you can pick either "log in with email (email goes in, local-part everywhere else, transformer + resolver do the conversion)" or "log in with sAMAccountName (one identifier all the way through, no bridging code at all)." Both work; the second is simpler if the user-typing pattern allows it.

