Three real issues that will bite you on startup, plus container-specific stuff that matters since you said this is the pre-image-build version.

Real issues
The auth.providers.ldap block has the wrong shape. You've nested ldapOrg.default.<config> inside it — that's the catalog provider shape. The auth provider expects a flat config under an environment name. It should be:

yaml
auth:
  environment: development
  providers:
    ldap:
      development:
        cookies:
          secure: false
          field: 'backstage-token'
        ldapAuthenticationOptions:
          userSearchBase: 'OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          usernameAttribute: 'sAMAccountName'
          adminDn: 'CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          adminPassword: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET}
          ldapOpts:
            url: 'ldaps://10.88.1.121:636'
    guest: {}
As written, the auth plugin won't find its config under development: and either crashes at startup or quietly falls back to defaults that don't talk to AD at all. The shape you wrote (with ldapOrg.default) is what belongs in the catalog providers.ldapOrg block — and that block is missing entirely from your file, which is the next issue.

The catalog has no LDAP provider configured. You removed the whole catalog.providers.ldapOrg block. That means nothing is ingesting Users from AD into the catalog — your sign-in will succeed, then checkUserExists will return false because the User entity doesn't exist, and login will fail with "user not found." Add it back:

yaml
catalog:
  providers:
    ldapOrg:
      default:
        target: ldaps://10.88.1.121:636
        bind:
          dn: CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in
          secret: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET}
        users:
          - dn: OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in
            options:
              filter: (&(objectClass=user)(!(objectClass=computer)))
            map:
              rdn: cn
              name: sAMAccountName
              displayName: displayName
              email: mail
  import:
    ...
Two separate blocks — one for auth, one for catalog — each with the full LDAP connection details (URL, bind DN, secret). They're independent because they're different plugins.

Secrets in plaintext. Three of them in your file: AD bind password, GitLab PAT, Jenkins API token. They're now committed to chat. Rotate all three before the image builds, and use env-var refs in the YAML so the image can't carry credentials:

yaml
bind:
  secret: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET}
# ...
gitlab:
  - host: gitlab.com
    token: ${GITLAB_TOKEN}
# ...
productionRequests:
  jenkins:
    apiToken: ${PR_JENKINS_API_TOKEN}
  gitlab:
    apiToken: ${PR_GITLAB_API_TOKEN}
This is also what lets the image be the same across environments — secrets get injected at run-time via env, not baked in.

Container/image considerations
Now that you're packaging this up:

baseUrls become wrong. http://localhost:3000 and http://localhost:7007 will be incorrect the moment the image runs anywhere that isn't your laptop. The whole point of the env-var pattern Backstage's app-config uses is so the same image runs in dev, staging, and prod with different URLs. Switch to:

yaml
app:
  baseUrl: ${APP_BASE_URL}
backend:
  baseUrl: ${BACKEND_BASE_URL}
cors:
  origin: ${APP_BASE_URL}
Same for productionRequests.jenkins.baseUrl and productionRequests.argocd.baseUrl — these point at localhost:8080/8081 which won't exist inside a container. Move them to ${PR_JENKINS_BASE_URL} and ${PR_ARGOCD_BASE_URL} so each environment configures the real hostnames.

The database is in-memory. connection: ':memory:' means every container restart wipes all production requests. Fine for the first test run; not fine the moment you care about persistence. Either point it at a file under a mounted volume:

yaml
database:
  client: better-sqlite3
  connection: '/data/production-requests.db'
or switch to Postgres now (single config change; the codebase doesn't care). For a deployable image, file-backed is the minimum; Postgres is the real answer.

The examples/*.yaml catalog locations use ../../examples/... paths. Inside the image, the working directory and the location of the bundled YAML files will differ from your dev tree. The standard pattern is to ship those YAML files inside the image (e.g. at /app/examples/) and reference them as absolute paths or under ${EXAMPLES_DIR}/.... Otherwise the catalog loader will log "file not found" warnings for each one on startup.

LDAPS certificate trust. Your AD is ldaps:// (port 636). Inside the image, Node will refuse the TLS handshake unless the issuing CA is trusted. Two options for the Dockerfile: copy your internal CA cert into the image (COPY internal-ca.crt /etc/ssl/certs/) and set ENV NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS=/etc/ssl/certs/internal-ca.crt, or for early POC ENV NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0 (only for non-prod). The symptom of getting this wrong is "unable to verify the first certificate" on LDAP refresh in the logs.

auth.providers.guest should be off in non-dev builds. Right now anyone visiting your portal can click "Continue as guest" and bypass LDAP entirely. Use a production config (or just delete the guest block) before the image ships beyond local testing:

yaml
auth:
  environment: ${AUTH_ENVIRONMENT}     # 'development' locally, 'production' otherwise
  providers:
    ldap:
      development:  # ... your dev LDAP
      production:   # ... your prod LDAP, possibly the same
    # no guest here
