The error is about the build context, not the build itself. Look at what Docker is being told to package:

docker build -t bst-upihelp:1.0.1 ./packages/backend
                                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
                                  this is the build context
You pointed the context at ./packages/backend. That means Docker only has access to files inside ./packages/backend/. But the Dockerfile is trying to COPY paths from above that — .yarn, .yarnrc.yml, backstage.json, yarn.lock, package.json, examples/, and packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz. All of those live at the monorepo root, and from inside the ./packages/backend context they don't exist (/packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz from a packages/backend context is asking for packages/backend/packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz).

That's literally what the last line says: "/packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz": not found. It's looking for a packages/backend/dist/... inside packages/backend/.

Fix: run the build from the monorepo root, with . as the context and the Dockerfile path made explicit:

bash
docker build -t bst-upihelp:1.0.1 -f packages/backend/Dockerfile .
The -f packages/backend/Dockerfile tells Docker which Dockerfile to use, and the trailing . says "build context is the current directory" — which from the root is everything the Dockerfile's COPY lines actually expect. Run that from C:\Users\npci\alpha\latest\bst-fork (your monorepo root, where package.json and yarn.lock live).

The reason it's wired this way: the Dockerfile is set up for the multi-package build pattern Backstage uses. It needs root-level files (yarn.lock, .yarn/, etc.) so it can do a workspace-aware production install, and it needs the bundle from packages/backend/dist/ produced by yarn build:backend. Both live in different folders, so the context has to be the common ancestor — the root.

Two things to confirm before re-running, since the COPY paths assume they exist:

bash
ls packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz
ls packages/backend/dist/skeleton.tar.gz
If those don't exist, yarn build:backend didn't produce them — you'd need to re-run it (yarn build:backend or yarn workspace backend build depending on your monorepo's script names). Both files are normal outputs of a Backstage backend bundle build.

And a .dockerignore at the root is worth a glance — your build log shows transferring context: 2B, which is suspiciously tiny. That suggests your .dockerignore is excluding almost everything (or your context was already pointing at the wrong place, which lines up with the original mistake). Once you switch to the root context, .dockerignore will determine what actually gets shipped to the Docker daemon; a typical one excludes node_modules, .git, etc. but lets the dist/skeleton tarballs and root files through.

So the one-line fix is the context change. Run that and the COPY errors will resolve in order.

