10 Jun
Three signals in that error, and together they point at one cause: DNS isn't resolving from the machine you're pushing from. Specifically lookup registry-1.docker.io: no such host means the OS can't translate Docker Hub's hostname to an IP — which is upstream of TLS, of auth, of registry permissions. None of the Docker-side things matter until DNS works.

Three plausible reasons, easy to diagnose in order:

You're on a corporate/proxy-restricted network without the proxy configured for Docker. That's the most likely one given the error literally says "no HTTPS proxy" — the message is Docker telling you it tried to go direct because no proxy is set, but the direct path can't resolve DNS either, because your network only allows DNS through the proxy. Standard NPCI-style setup. Confirm by trying:

powershell
nslookup registry-1.docker.io
If that also says no such host or times out, it's the network. If it resolves, DNS is fine and we look elsewhere.

If it's the proxy, you set Docker Desktop's proxy in Settings → Resources → Proxies, fill in your corporate HTTP/HTTPS proxy URL there, apply, restart Docker Desktop, and try the push again. That writes the right config into Docker's daemon. Doing it via shell env vars won't fix Docker Desktop because the daemon is a separate process.

Docker Desktop itself isn't running, or the daemon isn't talking to its DNS. Less likely given other docker commands worked for the build, but a quick docker info will confirm — if it returns something, the daemon is alive. If docker info itself errors, restart Docker Desktop and retry.

You're not logged in. Different error usually (unauthorized: incorrect username or password), but worth ruling out — does docker login succeed? If it can't even log in with the same hostname-not-found error, definitely DNS/proxy. If login works but push fails, you've isolated the problem to large-blob uploads, which sometimes hit different endpoints — but again, your error message points at the basic hostname, so I'd bet on the proxy.

The fastest one-line diagnostic: try curl https://registry-1.docker.io/v2/ from the same shell. Three possible outcomes:

"could not resolve host" → DNS/proxy problem. Configure Docker's proxy in Settings.
"401 Unauthorized" with a JSON body → DNS and network are fine, the registry just wants auth. Run docker login and retry the push.
Hangs and times out → network reachable to DNS but blocked at the firewall. Talk to network admin or use a tunnel.
The fact that docker build worked earlier but docker push fails on DNS is normal in this scenario — build pulls base images, which Docker Desktop may have cached, or which went through a different endpoint already in your hosts file. Push requires a fresh connection out to the auth+registry hosts, and those need DNS at request time.

