Good news in two parts: DNS is clearly fine now (you got plenty of IPs back), and the push has progressed. Most layers already exist, and you're now failing on a single layer upload mid-stream with 400 Bad request. That's a completely different problem from the DNS one and much narrower.

The 400 on a PUT blobs/uploads/<uuid> mid-upload is almost always one of three things:

Free storage on your Docker Hub account. If you're on the free tier, accounts have a (small) storage limit — when you hit it, the upload of the next blob gets rejected partway through with a 400, even though everything up to that blob succeeded. Quick check: log into hub.docker.com → your repositories → look at total storage used. If you've been pushing big images repeatedly, you may be at the cap. Delete an old image or two and retry.

Layer is too large for a single PUT, or the session expired. That URL in the error has ExpiresAt: 2026-06-10T11:24:08 — a 30-minute window. Your layer is 117.9 MB and it stopped at 20 MB. On a slow corporate link, you may genuinely have hit the expiry while uploading. Cure for this is docker push resuming, but Docker's resume logic is fragile; the practical workaround is simply to retry — the layers that succeeded are already on the registry (you'll see them all jump straight to "Layer already exists" on the next attempt), so you only re-upload the failed one and whatever's after.

An intermediate proxy/firewall is corrupting or truncating the upload. Common on corporate networks where the proxy has a body-size limit or a write timeout. Symptom is exactly this: small layers go through, the big one dies. If you're behind your office proxy, this is plausible. Less you can do here without network-team help, but seeing if a personal hotspot pushes the same image successfully proves it.

The thing to try first, because it's free and often works:

powershell
docker push neuron5ai/bst-upihelp:1.0.1
…just again. Seriously. The successful layers are now cached on the registry side, so it'll skip them and try the failed one fresh with a new upload session. Two or three retries clear most of these on flaky networks.

If retries keep dying on the same layer, that's a stronger signal it's either the storage quota or a proxy truncation rather than transient flakiness. Then:

powershell
docker images neuron5ai/bst-upihelp:1.0.1
…tells you the total image size. If it's a few hundred MB, you're well within any reasonable quota and the suspect shifts to the network/proxy. If it's pushing past a gigabyte, the free-tier ceiling becomes likely.

One more practical angle while you debug: Backstage backend images tend to bloat because the build pattern copies the whole production node_modules into the image. If pushing this size repeatedly is going to be a pain on your network, you can usually halve the image by switching to a multi-stage Dockerfile (one stage installs and bundles, the final stage copies only the bundle and slim node_modules). Not urgent — get this one pushed first — but worth knowing as the long-term fix if "push takes forever" keeps being a thing.

So: retry once or twice, check Hub's storage gauge if it keeps failing, and only escalate to proxy/firewall theories if both rule out. What does a second push attempt do — same layer, same point, or somewhere new?

