1.8 GB is the answer to two questions at once: why the push keeps failing and what to fix. That's a very large image for a Backstage backend — and on a corporate connection, pushing 1.8 GB through a proxy that probably has a body-size or timeout limit means the upload genuinely can't complete in one session. Retrying with the same image is going to keep dying the same way.

The two paths are "make the push survive" or "make the image smaller." Make it smaller — it's the right fix, and you'll thank yourself every subsequent push.

Why your image is 1.8 GB. A typical Backstage backend image is 300–500 MB. The usual reasons you blow past that are:

The build tools (python3, g++, build-essential, libsqlite3-dev from your Dockerfile) are needed to compile native modules like better-sqlite3 during install, but you don't need them at runtime. If they're still in the final image, that alone is hundreds of MB of compilers you'll never use.

yarn workspaces focus --all --production installs production deps only, which is good, but if it ran before/alongside compilation in a single stage, the build artifacts and source remain.

Your skeleton + bundle tarballs get extracted into the image and the tar files themselves may or may not be cleaned up cleanly.

If node_modules at the root and per-package node_modules both end up in the image (workspace hoisting can leave duplicates if focus doesn't dedupe perfectly), that's another big chunk.

The right fix: multi-stage build. Compile in a fat builder stage, then copy only the runtime artifacts into a slim final stage. The compiler images, intermediate caches, and tarballs never reach the layer that gets pushed. Sketch:

dockerfile
# ---- builder ----
FROM node:24-trixie-slim AS builder
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
      python3 g++ build-essential libsqlite3-dev && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
WORKDIR /app

COPY .yarn ./.yarn
COPY .yarnrc.yml backstage.json yarn.lock package.json ./
COPY packages/backend/dist/skeleton.tar.gz ./
RUN tar xzf skeleton.tar.gz && rm skeleton.tar.gz
RUN yarn workspaces focus --all --production

COPY packages/backend/dist/bundle.tar.gz app-config*.yaml ./
RUN tar xzf bundle.tar.gz && rm bundle.tar.gz

COPY examples ./examples

# ---- runtime ----
FROM node:24-trixie-slim
WORKDIR /app
# only the small runtime deps, no compilers
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
      libsqlite3-0 ca-certificates && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# bring over just the built application + production node_modules
COPY --from=builder --chown=node:node /app /app

USER node
CMD ["node", "packages/backend", "--config", "app-config.yaml"]
The two changes that matter: the final stage uses libsqlite3-0 (the runtime library, ~1 MB) instead of libsqlite3-dev (headers + compiler bits, much larger), and it omits python3, g++, build-essential entirely. By the time better-sqlite3 is installed in the builder stage, its native binary lives in node_modules/better-sqlite3/build/, so the runtime stage just inherits the already-compiled artifact and never needs the compiler again.

Realistic outcome: this typically gets you from 1.8 GB down to 400–600 MB. Still chunky (it's a full Node stack with hundreds of packages), but pushable.

A faster band-aid if you need the push to land today before refactoring the Dockerfile: push from a network without a proxy/firewall (personal hotspot, home connection). It bypasses the proxy interaction that's probably truncating your upload. Confirms whether the corporate network is the actual blocker, and lets you ship while you optimize. Not a fix, a workaround.

Things not to bother trying:

docker push --max-concurrent-uploads=1 — sometimes suggested for flaky pushes; it slows things down but doesn't fix size or quota issues.

Splitting the image into smaller tags — Docker pushes by layer, not by tag, so this is just shuffling the same data.

Pushing one layer at a time manually — Docker doesn't expose this; the push is atomic per blob.

So the order I'd suggest: rebuild with a multi-stage Dockerfile, check the new size with docker images, retry the push. If the size hasn't dropped much, post your docker images output and I can suggest more targeted trims (it sometimes turns out the examples/ folder or a build cache ended up in the image by accident, which is a cheap fix).

What's the slowest realistic part of this — refactoring the Dockerfile, or finding a non-proxy network to do a one-time push from while you optimize?

