The build failed on the cleanup line, not the install — and the reason is right there: rm: cannot remove '/home/node/.cache/yarn': Device or resource busy. You're trying to rm -rf a directory that's a mounted cache volume. It's mounted into the container at that path by the --mount=type=cache directive, so you can't delete the mountpoint itself — it's busy because the mount is live. That's what returns exit code 1 and aborts.

The fix: don't try to delete the mount. The whole point of --mount=type=cache is that the cache lives outside the image — it never gets baked into a layer in the first place. So deleting it is both impossible (busy) and unnecessary (it's not in your image anyway). Drop it from the rm:

dockerfile
RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/home/node/.cache/yarn,sharing=locked \
    yarn workspaces focus --all --production && \
    yarn cache clean && \
    rm -rf /tmp/*
Changes from your version: removed /home/node/.cache/yarn from the rm (it's the busy mountpoint), and replaced the weird rm -rf "$(yarn cache clean)" with a plain yarn cache clean. That $(...) construct was trying to rm whatever path yarn cache clean prints — fragile and pointless when the cache is a mount. yarn cache clean on its own does the cleanup; and since the cache is mounted, even that is mostly moot for image size. The rm -rf /tmp/* is the only cleanup that actually shrinks the layer (clears extraction temp files).

There are also two warnings in that log worth understanding, even though neither is what failed the build:

cpu-features couldn't be built successfully (exit code 1) — this is a transitive native dependency (it comes in via ssh2, used by some git/SSH features). It failed to compile, but the build continued past it, which means it's an optional native dep — the JS falls back to a pure-JS path when the native build fails. So it's a warning, not fatal. If you later see SSH-related features misbehaving you'd revisit it, but for now it's benign and not your blocker.

backend doesn't provide react ... requested by @immobiliarelabs/backstage-plugin-ldap-auth-backend — a peer-dependency warning. The LDAP auth backend plugin lists react as a peer dep (slightly odd for a backend plugin, but some shared Backstage packages drag it in), and your backend workspace doesn't have react as a direct dependency. It's a warning, not an error — the plugin will still load. If it ever causes a runtime "cannot find module react," you'd add react to the backend's package.json, but don't pre-emptively; it's just noise right now.

typescript patch: Cannot apply hunk #1 — also a warning; Yarn couldn't apply its TypeScript compatibility patch cleanly, usually a version-skew thing. Doesn't affect the production runtime image (TS is a dev concern), so ignore for this build.

So: the one real fix is the rm line. Make that change and rebuild:

powershell
docker build -t neuron5ai/bst-upihelp:1.0.2 -f packages/backend/Dockerfile .
It should clear the cleanup step and proceed to the second stage. If the cpu-features warning bothers you later or SSH features break, that's a separate, optional thread to pull — but it won't stop this build.

