Two separate startup failures, both straightforward — they're the production-environment versions of config that only existed for development locally.

Error 1: missing required config value at auth.providers.ldap.production

Your container runs with app-config.production.yaml layered on top (that's the second --config in your CMD), and the auth environment there is production. But your auth.providers.ldap block only has a development: sub-key. The auth plugin looks for auth.providers.ldap.production and finds nothing.

You need a production: block under ldap. In app-config.production.yaml:

yaml
auth:
  environment: production
  providers:
    ldap:
      production:
        cookies:
          secure: false        # set true if serving over HTTPS
          field: 'backstage-token'
        ldapAuthenticationOptions:
          userSearchBase: 'OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          usernameAttribute: 'sAMAccountName'
          adminDn: 'CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          adminPassword: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET}
          ldapOpts:
            url: 'ldaps://10.88.1.121:636'
The dev block in app-config.yaml stays; this adds the production equivalent. Same connection details, just under production: because environment: production. (Also drop the guest: {} provider in production — you don't want guest login on a real deployment.)

Error 2: no schedule provided neither via config nor via code for the LDAP catalog module.

The LDAP catalog provider needs a refresh schedule — how often it re-scrapes AD. Locally it apparently ran without one (older versions defaulted; current ones require it explicitly). You add a schedule block to the provider config:

yaml
catalog:
  providers:
    ldapOrg:
      default:
        target: ldaps://10.88.1.121:636
        bind:
          dn: 'CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          secret: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET}
        users:
          - dn: 'OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
            options:
              filter: (&(objectClass=user)(!(objectClass=computer)))
            map:
              rdn: cn
              name: sAMAccountName
              displayName: displayName
              email: mail
        schedule:
          frequency: { minutes: 60 }
          timeout: { minutes: 15 }
          initialDelay: { seconds: 30 }
The schedule tells the catalog "re-ingest users from LDAP every 60 minutes, give each run up to 15 minutes, wait 30 seconds after startup before the first run." Those numbers are reasonable defaults — frequency is how often, timeout is the kill-switch if a run hangs, initialDelay staggers it so it doesn't fire the instant the backend boots.

The root cause of both: your app-config.production.yaml is incomplete — it's missing the production auth block and (apparently) the catalog provider schedule. The container loads app-config.yaml then app-config.production.yaml on top, and environment: production flips it to look for production-keyed config that isn't there.

Two ways to fix, pick one:

Option A — put the full config in app-config.production.yaml. Add the production: auth block and the schedule: to that file, rebuild the image (or mount the config), redeploy. Cleanest for a real deployment, since production config is meant to differ from dev.

Option B — for a quick test, run with only the dev config. Drop the --config app-config.production.yaml from the CMD so it runs environment: development, which already has the working auth block. You'd still need to add the schedule: (that error is environment-independent — the catalog provider needs a schedule in dev too, you just didn't hit it before because... actually you should have. Worth checking your local app-config.yaml has the schedule and it simply wasn't copied into the image).

