Two problems here, one structural and one that you may not actually want.

The schedule: block is in the wrong place. You've put it inside the auth provider (auth.providers.ldap.production.schedule). But the "no schedule provided" error came from the catalog LDAP module, not auth. The auth provider doesn't take a schedule — it authenticates on-demand when someone logs in, there's nothing to schedule. So this schedule: block is sitting in a spot where it does nothing, and the catalog module still has no schedule, so error 2 will persist.

The schedule: belongs under catalog.providers.ldapOrg.default, not here:

yaml
catalog:
  providers:
    ldapOrg:
      default:
        target: ldaps://10.88.1.121:636
        bind:
          dn: 'CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          secret: 'Securegen@229933$'
        users:
          - dn: 'OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
            options:
              filter: (&(objectClass=user)(!(objectClass=computer)))
            map:
              rdn: cn
              name: sAMAccountName
              displayName: displayName
              email: mail
        schedule:                          # <-- HERE, under the catalog provider
          frequency: { minutes: 60 }
          timeout: { minutes: 15 }
          initialDelay: { seconds: 30 }
So your auth block loses the schedule: entirely, and the catalog block (in whichever config file holds it) gains it. Make sure the catalog provider block is also present in app-config.production.yaml (or in the base app-config.yaml that loads underneath it) — if it only exists in the dev file and not in production, the module won't find it at all.

Cleaned-up auth block:

yaml
auth:
  environment: production
  providers:
    ldap:
      production:
        cookies:
          secure: false
          field: 'backstage-token'
        ldapAuthenticationOptions:
          userSearchBase: 'OU=NPCI Users,OU=NPCI,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          usernameAttribute: 'sAMAccountName'
          adminDn: 'CN=Hadoop Admin,OU=Server Service Account,OU=Servers,DC=npci,DC=org,DC=in'
          adminPassword: 'Securegen@229933$'
          ldapOpts:
            url: 'ldaps://10.88.1.121:636'
The guest: {} — do you really want it in production? You've kept it. With guest enabled, anyone who reaches the portal can click "Continue as guest" and skip LDAP entirely. For a real deployment that defeats the point of the auth you just built. I removed it above. If you're keeping it deliberately as a fallback while you confirm LDAP works end-to-end on the Linux box, that's a reasonable temporary choice — just remember to pull it once login is verified. If you want it gone now, the block above already has it removed.

Two more things that will bite on the Linux box:

cookies.secure: false is fine only if you're serving over plain HTTP. The moment this is behind HTTPS (which production usually is), browsers will refuse to send a non-secure cookie over a secure connection and login will appear to "work then immediately log out." If the Linux deployment is HTTPS, set secure: true.

The plaintext adminPassword: 'Securegen@229933$' — this is the AD service account password sitting in a config file inside your image. Beyond the "it's in this chat, rotate it" point from before, baking it into the image means anyone who can docker pull or inspect the image layers can read it. The env-var pattern (adminPassword: ${LDAP_BIND_SECRET} and pass -e LDAP_BIND_SECRET=... at docker run) keeps it out of the image. Strongly worth doing for an AD service account credential specifically, since that account can read your whole directory.

So the fixes in order: move schedule: from the auth block to the catalog provider block, confirm the catalog provider block actually exists in the production config, decide on guest, and ideally move that AD password to an env var. The schedule relocation is the one that clears your error 2 — the rest are correctness/security.

