Yes, you can open CORS up — and for an AWB/custom-browser setup where you're not certain what origin the browser presents, it's a reasonable debugging move. But there's an important catch with your specific config that will make a naive "allow all" silently fail, so let me give you the version that actually works.

The catch: you have credentials: true. When credentials are enabled, the CORS spec forbids the wildcard * origin — browsers reject Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * together with Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true. So you can't just write origin: '*' and call it done; the browser will block it precisely because credentials are on. And you need credentials on, because that's how the auth cookie/token rides along with API calls.

The way to "allow all" with credentials is to reflect the request's origin back rather than wildcard it. Backstage's CORS config accepts a few forms; the ones that work with credentials:

yaml
backend:
  cors:
    origin: true        # reflects whatever Origin the request sends, and works with credentials
    methods: [GET, HEAD, PATCH, POST, PUT, DELETE]
    credentials: true
origin: true tells the underlying CORS middleware "echo back the incoming Origin header as the allowed origin." Functionally that's "allow any origin," but done in the credential-safe way (each response says Access-Control-Allow-Origin: <that exact origin> instead of *). This is the right knob for your "I don't know what origin AWB presents" situation.

If origin: true doesn't parse in your Backstage version (the config schema sometimes wants a string or list), the fallback is to list the specific origins:

yaml
cors:
  origin:
    - http://10.1.149.10:5705
    - http://localhost:5705
