Which means the real task is finding that origin, not wildcarding it. The browser tells you precisely. In the AWB browser, open dev tools (F12) → Network tab → trigger a failing API call (just reload the page) → click any request going to your backend → look at Request Headers → find the Origin: line. That exact string — scheme + host + port — is what must go in the origin array. In a proxied/custom-browser setup it's frequently not what you'd guess; it might be the AWB gateway's address, a different port, or even null in some sandboxed embeddings.

A couple of research-backed specifics for edge cases you might hit:

If the Network tab shows Origin: null (happens in some sandboxed iframes or certain proxy configurations), you genuinely can't match it with a normal origin string — null as an allowed origin is a known security footgun and Backstage's schema won't let you whitelist it nicely. That situation usually means the AWB is wrapping the app in a way that strips the origin, and the fix is on the AWB/proxy side (configuring it to preserve the origin), not in Backstage config.

If there's no Origin header at all on the requests, then CORS isn't even your problem — same-origin requests don't send an Origin header and aren't subject to CORS. In that case a failing request is something else (the baseUrl routing or the auth 404), and changing cors.origin will do nothing. This is worth confirming before you spend more time on CORS: if the frontend and backend are served from the same origin (which they are in your single-port image — both on :5705), then the frontend's calls to its own backend aren't cross-origin at all, and CORS isn't involved. That's likely your actual situation given everything serves off 5705.

