Here's a single regex that matches all those hosts (localhost, 127.0.0.1, and 10.1.149.13), any port, with or without the http:// scheme:

yaml
backend:
  cors:
    origin: /^(https?:\/\/)?(localhost|127\.0\.0\.1|10\.1\.149\.13)(:\d+)?$/
    methods: [GET, HEAD, PATCH, POST, PUT, DELETE]
    credentials: true
Breaking down what it matches so you can adjust it:

(https?:\/\/)? — optional http:// or https:// (the ? after the group makes the whole scheme optional, the s? allows both http and https).

(localhost|127\.0\.0\.1|10\.1\.149\.13) — any one of the three hosts. The dots are escaped (\.) so they match literal dots, not "any character."

(:\d+)? — optional : followed by any number of digits, i.e. any port or no port at all.

^...$ — anchors so it matches the whole origin string, not just a piece of it (important — without anchors, evil-10.1.149.13.com would sneak through).

If you want it to also cover the other hosts you've seen AWB use (you've mentioned both 10.1.149.10 and 10.1.149.13 across messages), widen the host group:

yaml
origin: /^(https?:\/\/)?(localhost|127\.0\.0\.1|10\.1\.149\.\d+)(:\d+)?$/
That 10\.1\.149\.\d+ matches any address in the 10.1.149.x range, which is probably safest given your addresses keep shifting around in that subnet.

