The build (yarn build:backend) compiles only code. It produces bundle.tar.gz (your compiled TypeScript) and skeleton.tar.gz. It does not embed your production config. That's why the app-config*.yaml files are copied separately in the Dockerfile (COPY ... app-config*.yaml ./) and loaded at container start via the --config flags in your CMD. So your CORS values, the single URL, the LDAP config — all of that is read fresh when the container boots, from the YAML files sitting in the image. Change a YAML, you don't even need to rebuild the code — just get the new YAML into the container and restart. (You do need to rebuild the image to update the YAML inside it, unless you mount it.)

The one exception — and it's an important one for you — is the frontend app build. Look at the very top of your log:

app: Loaded config from app-config.yaml
The frontend bundle is built with config baked in, because the browser can't read server-side YAML at runtime — values like app.baseUrl and backend.baseUrl get compiled into the JavaScript. And notice which file it loaded: app-config.yaml — your base/dev config, not app-config.production.yaml. So the frontend bundle currently has the dev baseUrl (http://localhost:3000 / http://localhost:7007) compiled into it, not your production http://10.1.149.10:5705.

